    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a good ROI percentage?</summary>
        <p>A "good" ROI depends entirely on the context. For stock market investments, the S&amp;P 500 has historically averaged about 10% annual returns before inflation. Real estate investors typically target 8&ndash;12% annual ROI. Marketing campaigns often aim for 5:1 return (400% ROI). A savings account earning 4&ndash;5% APY is considered good for risk-free returns. Always compare your ROI against the relevant benchmark for your investment type and factor in risk &mdash; higher returns usually come with higher risk.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between ROI and IRR?</summary>
        <p>ROI (Return on Investment) gives you a simple total percentage return without considering the time period or when cash flows occur. IRR (Internal Rate of Return) accounts for the time value of money and finds the annualized rate at which the net present value of all cash flows equals zero. IRR is better for comparing investments with different time horizons or irregular cash flows, such as real estate projects with varying rental income. ROI is easier to calculate and understand for straightforward, single-period investments.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can ROI be negative?</summary>
        <p>Yes, ROI can absolutely be negative, and it simply means you lost money on the investment. If you bought shares for $10,000 and sold them for $7,000, your ROI would be ($7,000 &minus; $10,000) / $10,000 = &minus;30%. A negative ROI tells you that the net profit was actually a net loss. This is common in business ventures, marketing campaigns that underperform, and market downturns.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you calculate ROI for real estate?</summary>
        <p>For real estate, ROI is calculated as (Annual Rental Income &minus; Annual Expenses) / Total Investment Cost &times; 100. Total investment cost includes the purchase price, closing costs, renovation costs, and any other upfront expenses. Annual expenses include property taxes, insurance, maintenance, property management fees, and mortgage interest. For a more complete picture, also consider appreciation, tax benefits, and equity buildup from mortgage principal payments. The cap rate (Net Operating Income / Property Price) is a related metric commonly used for comparing rental properties.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do you calculate annualized ROI?</summary>
        <p>Annualized ROI converts a total return into an equivalent annual rate, making it possible to compare investments held for different periods. The formula is: Annualized ROI = ((1 + Total ROI)<sup>1/n</sup> &minus; 1) &times; 100, where n is the number of years. For example, if you earned a 50% total return over 3 years, the annualized ROI would be ((1.50)<sup>1/3</sup> &minus; 1) &times; 100 = 14.47% per year. This is more accurate than simply dividing the total return by the number of years because it accounts for compounding.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

